        "title": "Pregunta N°1",
        "code": "MAT1610-4-1 (24-2)",
        "content": "Sea la función\n\n$$f(x) = \\frac{x}{2 + x^2}$$\n\n¿Cuánto vale su derivada evaluada en $\\sqrt{2}$, es decir, $f'(\\sqrt{2})$?",
        "options": [
          { "label": "a", "text": "$0$" },
          { "label": "b", "text": "$\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt{2}}$" },
          { "label": "c", "text": "$\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$" },
          { "label": "d", "text": "$\\dfrac{1}{4}$" }
        ],
        "answer": "a",
        "solution": "Usando la regla del cociente:\n\n$$f'(x) = \\frac{(2 + x^2) \\cdot 1 - x \\cdot 2x}{(2 + x^2)^2} = \\frac{2 + x^2 - 2x^2}{(2 + x^2)^2} = \\frac{2 - x^2}{(2 + x^2)^2}$$\n\nEvaluando en $x = \\sqrt{2}$:\n\n$$f'(\\sqrt{2}) = \\frac{2 - (\\sqrt{2})^2}{(2 + (\\sqrt{2})^2)^2} = \\frac{2 - 2}{(2 + 2)^2} = \\frac{0}{16} = 0$$"
      }
    ]
  },
